447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"oko 1447.","1496":"1496","1470":"1470.","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"cs":{"about 1447–":"okolo 1447–Zesnulá","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Zesnulá","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"okolo 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"about 1447–":"omkring 1447–Afdød","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Afdød","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"omkring 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1447–":"circa 1447–Overleden","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Overleden","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"circa 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1447–":"about 1447–Deceased","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Deceased","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"about 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kilham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Kilham (ER Yorks), Kilham in Cantley (WR Yorks), or Kilham in Kirknewton (Northumb)."],"variants":[{"name":"Killham","meanings":["English: from any of several places in northern England called Kilham, most of which are recorded as <i>Killum</i> in medieval documents, from an Old English prepositional phrase meaning ‘at the kilns’."]},{"name":"Killam","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire): variant of <b>Kilham</b>, a habitational name from any of the places in Northumberland and Yorkshire, so named either from Old English <i>cylnum</i> ‘(at) the kilns’, dative plural of <i>cyln</i>, or from Old English <i>cyln</i> ‘kiln’ or the personal name <i>Cylla</i> + Old Norse <i>holmr</i> ‘small island, water meadow’. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":8,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705201,"age":102,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":111,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Peter Kilham was born about 1447, in England. She had at least 1 son with Peter Kilham."},"et":{"about 1447–":"umbes 1447–Surnud","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Surnud","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"umbes 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1447–":"noin 1447–Kuollut","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"noin 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1447–":"environ 1447–Décédée","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Décédée","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"environ 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs Peter Kilham est née environ 1447, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Peter Kilham."},"de":{"about 1447–":"um 1447–Verstorben","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1447–Female":"1447–Verstorben","1558":"1558","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1530":"1530","about 1447":"um 1447","1496":"1496","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Mrs Peter Kilham wurde um 1447 in England geboren. Sie hat